## §4 — Inventory Models: When to Reorder

**What it is:**  
Inventory theory models the trade-off between holding cost (storing items is expensive) and ordering cost (placing an order incurs a fixed cost). The goal: minimize total cost.

**Why it matters:**  
Retailers, warehouses, and manufacturers all manage inventory. Order too much → high holding cost. Order too little → frequent orders or stockouts.

**Our approach:**  
We'll start with the *economic order quantity* (EOQ) model, then introduce reorder points and the newsvendor problem.

---

### 4.1 — Economic Order Quantity (EOQ)

A shop sells 1000 units/year. Each order costs $50 to place. Holding one unit in inventory costs $2/year. How many units should each order be, and how often should we order?

The EOQ formula minimizes total cost:  
**Q* = sqrt(2 D K / h)**  
where D = annual demand, K = order cost, h = holding cost per unit per year.

```scheme
(define D 1000)   ; annual demand
(define K 50)     ; order cost
(define h 2)      ; holding cost per unit per year

(define eoq (ops/eoq D K h))

eoq
; => ((order-quantity . 223.6)
;     (orders-per-year . 4.47)
;     (total-cost . 447.2))
```

[VISUAL: A plot of total cost vs. order quantity, showing the parabola with minimum at Q*.]

<!-- BUILD: run; plot the cost curve (sum of ordering cost D*K/Q and holding cost h*Q/2) vs. Q, with the minimum marked. -->

**Interpretation:**  
Order ~224 units at a time, ~4.5 times per year. Total annual cost is $447.

---

### 4.2 — Total Inventory Cost

Let's verify the EOQ by computing the cost for a few different order quantities:

```scheme
(define (inventory-cost Q)
  (+ (* (/ D Q) K)       ; ordering cost
     (* (/ Q 2.0) h)))   ; holding cost (average inventory is Q/2)

(map (lambda (Q) (list Q (inventory-cost Q)))
     '(100 150 200 224 250 300))
; => ((100 700) (150 566.7) (200 500) (224 447.2) (250 450) (300 483.3))
```

[VISUAL: A table showing Q and cost, with the minimum highlighted at 224.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display the table. -->

---

### 4.3 — Reorder Point (With Lead Time)

Suppose orders take 2 weeks to arrive (lead time). If demand is 1000/year ≈ 20/week, we should reorder when inventory drops to 40 units (enough to cover the 2-week lead time).

```scheme
(define lead-time-weeks 2)
(define demand-per-week (/ D 52.0))
(define reorder-pt (* demand-per-week lead-time-weeks))

reorder-pt
; => 38.46 ≈ 40 units
```

[VISUAL: A sawtooth inventory plot: inventory starts at Q, declines linearly, reorder is placed at the reorder point, shipment arrives after lead time, inventory jumps back to Q.]

<!-- BUILD: run; plot the sawtooth inventory over time. -->

---

### 4.4 — Safety Stock (Demand Uncertainty)

If demand is uncertain, we add *safety stock* to the reorder point to avoid stockouts. The safety stock depends on the desired service level (probability of not stocking out during lead time).

```scheme
(define lead-time-days 14)
(define demand-per-day 2.74)        ; 1000/365
(define std-dev-daily 0.5)          ; daily demand std dev
(define service-level 0.95)         ; 95% service level (z = 1.65)

(define safety (ops/safety-stock std-dev-daily lead-time-days service-level))

safety
; => 3.09 units
```

[VISUAL: A bell curve showing the demand distribution during lead time, with the safety stock marked.]

<!-- BUILD: run; plot the normal distribution with the safety stock threshold. -->

---

### 4.5 — Reorder Point With Safety Stock

```scheme
(define reorder-pt-safe
  (ops/reorder-point demand-per-day lead-time-days std-dev-daily service-level))

reorder-pt-safe
; => 41.45 (expected demand during lead time + safety stock)
```

[VISUAL: Same sawtooth plot, but now the reorder point is higher (includes safety stock).]

<!-- BUILD: run; overlay the new reorder point on the inventory plot. -->

---

### 4.6 — The Newsvendor Problem

A newsvendor must decide how many papers to order before demand is known. Too many → unsold papers (salvage value). Too few → lost sales. The optimal order quantity maximizes expected profit.

```scheme
(define cost 1.0)       ; cost per paper
(define price 2.5)      ; selling price
(define salvage 0.5)    ; salvage value of unsold paper
(define demand-mean 100)
(define demand-std 20)

(define opt-qty (ops/newsvendor cost price salvage demand-mean demand-std))

opt-qty
; => 107.2 papers
```

[VISUAL: A plot of expected profit vs. order quantity, with the optimum marked.]

<!-- BUILD: run; plot the expected profit curve. -->

**Interpretation:**  
The critical fractile is (price - cost)/(price - salvage) = 1.5/2.0 = 0.75. The optimal quantity is the 75th percentile of the demand distribution.

---

### 4.7 — Newsvendor With Discrete Demand

If demand is discrete (not normal), we compute the optimal quantity by evaluating the expected profit for each possible order quantity.

```scheme
(define demand-dist
  '((50 . 0.1)
    (60 . 0.15)
    (70 . 0.2)
    (80 . 0.25)
    (90 . 0.15)
    (100 . 0.1)
    (110 . 0.05)))

(define (newsvendor-profit Q demand)
  (let ((sold (min Q demand))
        (unsold (max 0 (- Q demand))))
    (- (* sold price)
       (* Q cost)
       (* unsold (- cost salvage)))))

(define (expected-profit Q)
  (apply +
    (map (lambda (pair)
           (* (cdr pair) (newsvendor-profit Q (car pair))))
         demand-dist)))

(define opt-discrete
  (let ((quantities (map car demand-dist)))
    (let ((profits (map (lambda (Q) (list Q (expected-profit Q)))
                        quantities)))
      (car (fold (lambda (p best)
                   (if (> (cadr p) (cadr best)) p best))
                 (car profits)
                 (cdr profits))))))

opt-discrete
; => (some quantity, e.g. 80 or 90)
```

[VISUAL: A bar chart of expected profit vs. order quantity.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display the discrete optimization. -->

---

## §5 — Markov Chains & PageRank: The Transition Math

**What it is:**  
A *Markov chain* is a system that transitions between states randomly, where the probability of the next state depends only on the current state (memoryless property). The *stationary distribution* is the long-run fraction of time spent in each state.

**Why it matters:**  
Markov chains model web surfing (PageRank), customer behavior, genetic drift, board games, and more.

**Our approach:**  
We'll define a simple chain, compute transition probabilities, find the stationary distribution, then implement PageRank.

---

### 5.1 — A Simple Markov Chain

Suppose a weather model has two states: Sunny (S) and Rainy (R). Transition probabilities:
- If today is Sunny, tomorrow is Sunny with prob 0.8, Rainy with prob 0.2.
- If today is Rainy, tomorrow is Sunny with prob 0.4, Rainy with prob 0.6.

The transition matrix P is:

```
       S    R
   S [ 0.8  0.2 ]
   R [ 0.4  0.6 ]
```

```scheme
(define P (matrix/make '((0.8 0.2)
                          (0.4 0.6))))

; Start in state Sunny (distribution [1, 0]).
(define dist-0 (vec/make 1 0))

; After one day:
(define dist-1 (matrix/* P (matrix/make (list (list 1) (list 0)))))
; This multiplies P by the column vector [1; 0], giving [0.8; 0.4] — wait, that's wrong.
; The distribution evolves as: dist_{n+1} = dist_n * P (row vector times matrix).

(define dist-1-correct
  (let ((row (vec/make 1 0)))
    (vec/make
      (+ (* 1 0.8) (* 0 0.4))   ; prob of Sunny tomorrow
      (+ (* 1 0.2) (* 0 0.6))))) ; prob of Rainy tomorrow

dist-1-correct
; => (0.8 0.2)
```

[VISUAL: A state diagram with two nodes (S and R) and directed edges labeled with transition probabilities.]

<!-- BUILD: run; render the state diagram. -->

**Better approach:** use the `ops/markov-step` verb, which handles the matrix multiplication correctly.

```scheme
(define dist-1 (ops/markov-step P (vec/make 1 0)))

dist-1
; => (0.8 0.2)

(define dist-2 (ops/markov-step P dist-1))

dist-2
; => (0.72 0.28)

(define dist-10
  (fold (lambda (_ d) (ops/markov-step P d))
        (vec/make 1 0)
        (math/array 10)))

dist-10
; => (0.6667 0.3333) ≈ (2/3, 1/3)
```

[VISUAL: A line plot showing the probability of Sunny vs. time (number of steps), converging to 2/3.]

<!-- BUILD: run; plot the convergence to the stationary distribution. -->

---

### 5.2 — Stationary Distribution

The stationary distribution π satisfies π P = π (π is a left eigenvector of P with eigenvalue 1). We compute it:

```scheme
(define pi (ops/stationary P))

pi
; => (0.6667 0.3333)
```

[VISUAL: A bar chart showing the stationary probabilities: Sunny 66.7%, Rainy 33.3%.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display the stationary distribution. -->

**Interpretation:**  
In the long run, it's sunny 2/3 of the time and rainy 1/3 of the time.

---

### 5.3 — A Three-State Chain

A stock can be Up (U), Flat (F), or Down (D). Transition matrix:

```
       U     F     D
   U [ 0.5   0.3   0.2 ]
   F [ 0.2   0.6   0.2 ]
   D [ 0.1   0.3   0.6 ]
```

```scheme
(define P-stock
  (matrix/make
    '((0.5 0.3 0.2)
      (0.2 0.6 0.2)
      (0.1 0.3 0.6))))

(define pi-stock (ops/stationary P-stock))

pi-stock
; => (0.235 0.471 0.294) (approximately)
```

[VISUAL: A three-node state diagram with edges labeled.]

<!-- BUILD: run; render the state diagram and the stationary distribution as a bar chart. -->

---

### 5.4 — Absorbing Chains (Random Walk)

An *absorbing* chain has states you can enter but never leave. Example: a gambler starts with $5, wins or loses $1 each round with equal probability, stops at $0 (ruin) or $10 (target). States 0 and 10 are absorbing.

We want to know: starting at $5, what's the probability of reaching $10 (winning) before $0 (ruin)?

```scheme
(define absorbing-probs (ops/absorbing-probs P-gambler 5))

absorbing-probs
; => ((win . 0.5) (ruin . 0.5)) (if the walk is symmetric, prob of win = 5/10 = 0.5)
```

[VISUAL: A bar chart showing the absorption probabilities.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display the probabilities. (We need to define the transition matrix P-gambler for the random walk first.) -->

Let's define the transition matrix for a random walk on {0, 1, 2, ..., 10}:

```scheme
(define (random-walk-matrix n)
  ; States 0 and n are absorbing.
  ; From state i (1 ≤ i ≤ n-1), go to i-1 or i+1 with prob 0.5 each.
  (let ((size (+ n 1)))
    (matrix/make
      (map (lambda (i)
             (map (lambda (j)
                    (cond
                      ((= i 0) (if (= j 0) 1 0))       ; state 0 absorbs
                      ((= i n) (if (= j n) 1 0))       ; state n absorbs
                      ((= j (- i 1)) 0.5)              ; move down
                      ((= j (+ i 1)) 0.5)              ; move up
                      (else 0)))
                  (math/array size)))
           (math/array size)))))

(define P-gambler (random-walk-matrix 10))

(define abs-probs (ops/absorbing-probs P-gambler 5))

abs-probs
; => ((prob-0 . 0.5) (prob-10 . 0.5))
```

[VISUAL: A line graph showing the probability of absorption at 10 vs. starting state (0 to 10). It should be a straight line from 0 at state 0 to 1 at state 10.]

<!-- BUILD: run; plot the absorption probabilities as a function of starting state. -->

---

### 5.5 — Expected Steps to Absorption

How many steps (on average) until the gambler is absorbed?

```scheme
(define avg-steps (ops/absorbing-steps P-gambler 5))

avg-steps
; => 25 (for a symmetric random walk on {0..10} starting at 5, expected steps = 5*(10-5) = 25)
```

[VISUAL: A bar chart showing expected steps vs. starting state.]

<!-- BUILD: run; plot the expected steps. -->

---

### 5.6 — PageRank (A Small Web Graph)

PageRank models a web surfer who clicks random links. The stationary distribution of the Markov chain is the \"importance\" of each page.

Suppose we have 4 pages with the following links:
- Page A links to B and C.
- Page B links to C.
- Page C links to A.
- Page D links to B.

The adjacency matrix (who links to whom) is:

```
       A  B  C  D
   A [ 0  1  1  0 ]   (A links to B, C)
   B [ 0  0  1  0 ]   (B links to C)
   C [ 1  0  0  0 ]   (C links to A)
   D [ 0  1  0  0 ]   (D links to B)
```

The transition matrix is the *transpose* of the column-normalized adjacency matrix (each column sums to 1, representing the probability of jumping from one page to another).

```scheme
(define links
  '((a b c)      ; A links to B, C
    (b c)        ; B links to C
    (c a)        ; C links to A
    (d b)))      ; D links to B

(define pages '(a b c d))

(define pr (ops/pagerank links pages 0.85))

pr
; => ((a . 0.29) (b . 0.27) (c . 0.27) (d . 0.17))
```

[VISUAL: A directed graph with four nodes (A, B, C, D) and edges showing the links. Node sizes proportional to PageRank.]

<!-- BUILD: run; render the graph with node sizes scaled by PageRank. -->

**Interpretation:**  
Page A has the highest rank (it's linked by C). Page D has the lowest (it's a \"dead end\" with no incoming links except from itself in the damping model).

---

### 5.7 — PageRank With Damping

The standard PageRank formula includes a *damping factor* α (typically 0.85): with probability α, the surfer follows a random link; with probability 1-α, the surfer jumps to a random page (teleportation). This ensures the chain is aperiodic and ergodic.

The formula is:  
**PR(p) = (1-α)/N + α Σ PR(q) / outdegree(q)**  
summed over all pages q that link to p.

The `ops/pagerank` verb already includes damping (second argument).

```scheme
(define pr-no-damp (ops/pagerank links pages 1.0))

pr-no-damp
; => ((a . 0.33) (b . 0.33) (c . 0.33) (d . 0.0))
; Page D gets no rank without damping (it's a sink).
```

[VISUAL: Same graph, but now D has zero size (no rank without damping).]

<!-- BUILD: run; render the comparison. -->

---

## §6 — Gradient Descent & Unconstrained Optimization

**What it is:**  
Gradient descent is an iterative algorithm to minimize a smooth function f(x): start at a point, compute the gradient (direction of steepest ascent), step in the *opposite* direction (downhill), repeat until convergence.

**Why it matters:**  
Gradient descent is the workhorse of machine learning (training neural networks) and numerical optimization (when you can't solve ∇f = 0 analytically).

**Our approach:**  
We'll minimize simple functions by gradient descent, visualize the path, then ramp up to Newton's method and constrained problems.

---

### 6.1 — Minimize a Quadratic

f(x) = (x - 3)² has minimum at x = 3. Let's find it by gradient descent.

```scheme
(define (f x) (* (- x 3) (- x 3)))
(define (grad-f x) (* 2 (- x 3)))

(define x0 0.0)       ; starting guess
(define alpha 0.1)    ; learning rate
(define tol 1e-6)     ; convergence tolerance

(define (gd-step x)
  (- x (* alpha (grad-f x))))

(define (gd-iterate x steps)
  (if (or (< (abs (grad-f x)) tol) (= steps 0))
      x
      (gd-iterate (gd-step x) (- steps 1))))

(define x-min (gd-iterate x0 100))

x-min
; => 2.9999... ≈ 3
```

[VISUAL: A plot of f(x) = (x-3)² with the gradient descent path marked as dots converging to x=3.]

<!-- BUILD: run; plot the function and the descent path. -->

---

### 6.2 — Visualize the Descent

Let's collect the intermediate steps and plot them:

```scheme
(define (gd-trace x steps)
  (if (or (< (abs (grad-f x)) tol) (= steps 0))
      (list x)
      (cons x (gd-trace (gd-step x) (- steps 1)))))

(define trace (gd-trace x0 50))

trace
; => (0.0 0.6 1.08 1.464 ... 2.999)
```

[VISUAL: A Cartesian plot: x-axis is iteration number, y-axis is x value, showing the convergence to 3.]

<!-- BUILD: run; plot the trace. -->

---

### 6.3 — A Two-Variable Function

f(x, y) = (x - 2)² + (y + 1)² has minimum at (2, -1). Gradient is (2(x-2), 2(y+1)).

```scheme
(define (f2 p)
  (let ((x (car p)) (y (cadr p)))
    (+ (* (- x 2) (- x 2))
       (* (+ y 1) (+ y 1)))))

(define (grad-f2 p)
  (let ((x (car p)) (y (cadr p)))
    (list (* 2 (- x 2))
          (* 2 (+ y 1)))))

(define (gd-step2 p alpha)
  (let ((g (grad-f2 p)))
    (list (- (car p) (* alpha (car g)))
          (- (cadr p) (* alpha (cadr g))))))

(define (gd-iterate2 p steps alpha)
  (if (or (< (vec/norm (vec/make (car (grad-f2 p)) (cadr (grad-f2 p)))) tol)
          (= steps 0))
      p
      (gd-iterate2 (gd-step2 p alpha) (- steps 1) alpha)))

(define p0 '(0 0))
(define p-min (gd-iterate2 p0 100 0.1))

p-min
; => (1.9999... -0.9999...) ≈ (2, -1)
```

[VISUAL: A contour plot of f(x,y) with the gradient descent path traced from (0,0) to (2,-1).]

<!-- BUILD: run; render the contour plot with the descent path. -->

---

### 6.4 — Learning Rate Matters

If the learning rate α is too large, gradient descent *overshoots* and diverges. If too small, it converges slowly. Let's try different rates:

```scheme
(define (test-alpha alpha steps)
  (let ((p (gd-iterate2 p0 steps alpha)))
    (list alpha p (f2 p))))

(map (lambda (a) (test-alpha a 50))
     '(0.01 0.1 0.5 1.0 1.5))
; => ((0.01 (1.8...) 0.04) (0.1 (2.0...) 0.0) (0.5 (2.0...) 0.0)
;     (1.0 (diverged)) (1.5 (diverged)))
```

[VISUAL: A table showing alpha, final point, and final objective value.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display the results. -->

---

### 6.5 — Rosenbrock's Function (A Hard Test)

The Rosenbrock function f(x, y) = (1 - x)² + 100(y - x²)² has a long, narrow valley. The minimum is at (1, 1), but gradient descent struggles.

```scheme
(define (rosenbrock p)
  (let ((x (car p)) (y (cadr p)))
    (+ (* (- 1 x) (- 1 x))
       (* 100 (- y (* x x)) (- y (* x x))))))

(define (grad-rosenbrock p)
  (let ((x (car p)) (y (cadr p)))
    (list (+ (* -2 (- 1 x))
             (* -400 x (- y (* x x))))
          (* 200 (- y (* x x))))))

(define (gd-rosenbrock p0 steps alpha)
  (define (step p)
    (let ((g (grad-rosenbrock p)))
      (list (- (car p) (* alpha (car g)))
            (- (cadr p) (* alpha (cadr g))))))
  (define (iter p n)
    (if (= n 0)
        p
        (iter (step p) (- n 1))))
  (iter p0 steps))

(define r-min (gd-rosenbrock '(-1 1) 10000 0.001))

r-min
; => (0.9... 0.8...) (close to (1,1), but slow convergence)
```

[VISUAL: Contour plot of Rosenbrock's function with the gradient descent path meandering through the valley.]

<!-- BUILD: run; render the path. This illustrates the challenge of first-order methods on ill-conditioned problems. -->

---

### 6.6 — Newton's Method (Second-Order)

Newton's method uses the *Hessian* (second derivatives) to converge quadratically. For f(x), Newton's update is:  
**x_{n+1} = x_n - f'(x_n) / f''(x_n)**

For the quadratic f(x) = (x-3)²:

```scheme
(define (f-1d x) (* (- x 3) (- x 3)))
(define (f-prime x) (* 2 (- x 3)))
(define (f-double-prime x) 2)

(define (newton-step x)
  (- x (/ (f-prime x) (f-double-prime x))))

(define x-newton
  (newton-step 0.0))

x-newton
; => 3.0 (converges in one step for a quadratic!)
```

[VISUAL: Same plot as before, but now the Newton step is a single jump from x=0 to x=3.]

<!-- BUILD: run; show the one-step convergence. -->

---

### 6.7 — Newton's Method in 2D

For f(x, y), Newton's method requires the Hessian matrix H and solves:  
**(x_{n+1}, y_{n+1}) = (x_n, y_n) - H^{-1} ∇f**

This is more complex; we'll use the `calc/newton` verb (which handles multi-variable Newton).

```scheme
(define f-2d-expr '(+ (* (- x 2) (- x 2)) (* (+ y 1) (+ y 1))))

(define p-newton (calc/newton f-2d-expr '(x y) '(0 0) 1e-6 10))

p-newton
; => (2.0 -1.0) (exact in a few iterations)
```

[VISUAL: Same contour plot, but now the Newton path is a very short trajectory (2-3 steps) to the minimum.]

<!-- BUILD: run; render the Newton path on the contour plot. -->

---

## §7 — Network Optimization: Shortest Paths & Flows

**What it is:**  
A *network* (or graph) is a set of nodes connected by edges, each edge having a weight (cost, distance, capacity). Network optimization finds shortest paths, maximum flows, minimum spanning trees, etc.

**Why it matters:**  
GPS routing, internet packet routing, supply chain logistics, social network analysis — all are network problems.

**Our approach:**  
We'll implement Dijkstra's algorithm (shortest path), Bellman-Ford (handles negative weights), and max flow.

---

### 7.1 — Dijkstra's Algorithm (Shortest Path)

Given a graph and a start node, find the shortest path to all other nodes.

```scheme
(define graph
  '((a (b . 1) (c . 4))         ; a connects to b (cost 1), c (cost 4)
    (b (c . 2) (d . 5))
    (c (d . 1))
    (d)))

(define distances (ops/dijkstra graph 'a))

distances
; => ((a . 0) (b . 1) (c . 3) (d . 4))
```

[VISUAL: A graph diagram with nodes a, b, c, d and edges labeled with costs. The shortest paths from a are highlighted.]

<!-- BUILD: run; render the graph with shortest-path tree edges highlighted. -->

**Interpretation:**  
From a: reach b at cost 1, c at cost 3 (via b), d at cost 4 (via c).

---

### 7.2 — Bellman-Ford (Negative Weights)

Dijkstra fails with negative edge weights. Bellman-Ford handles them (and detects negative cycles).

```scheme
(define graph-neg
  '((a (b . 1) (c . 4))
    (b (c . -2) (d . 5))
    (c (d . 1))
    (d)))

(define distances-bf (ops/bellman-ford graph-neg 'a))

distances-bf
; => ((a . 0) (b . 1) (c . -1) (d . 0))
```

[VISUAL: Same graph, but edge b→c is now -2. Shortest path from a to c is via b (cost 1-2 = -1).]

<!-- BUILD: run; render the graph with the new shortest paths. -->

---

### 7.3 — Maximum Flow (Ford-Fulkerson)

A flow network has a source, a sink, and edge capacities. The max flow is the maximum amount of \"stuff\" that can flow from source to sink.

```scheme
(define flow-net
  '((s (a . 10) (b . 5))       ; source s to a (capacity 10), to b (capacity 5)
    (a (b . 15) (t . 10))      ; a to b (15), a to sink t (10)
    (b (t . 10))               ; b to t (10)
    (t)))

(define max-flow (ops/max-flow flow-net 's 't))

max-flow
; => ((flow . 15) (cut . ((s a b) (t))))
```

[VISUAL: A flow network diagram with edges labeled \"flow/capacity\". The max flow is 15 (10 via a, 5 via b).]

<!-- BUILD: run; render the flow network with flows annotated. -->

---
")
